§ 1. The above copyright notice and this permission notice shall be included in all
   copies or substantial portions of the Software.

§ 2. If the Software or any derivative work is used in a commercial project, credit
   must be given to Mnemosyne Labs + Azoth Corp (the "Company"), and Logan Kirkland 
   (the "Original Author") as the original developers of the Software. Credit must 
   also be given generally to the community (the "Community") of any open source 
   contributors to the Software, including to the Prompt Engineers Guild (the "Guild").

§ 3. If the Software or any derivative work is used in a commercial project by an entity
   with yearly untaxed profits over $10 million, a 1.5% royalty on all revenues derived 
   from the Software must be paid (per annum, in perpetuity) to: the Company (0.5%), 
   the Original Author (0.5%), and the the Guild (0.5%). Annual payments must be made by December 31st of the same year.

§ 4. If royalties are not paid as stipulated in § 3, retroactive fees will be calculated at 
   2% per annum on the outstanding balance. Additionally, a penalty fee of $10,000 will be 
   applied for each year the royalties remain unpaid. Retroactive fees and penalties will be 
   divided equally among the Company, the Original Author, and the Guild.

§ 5. Azoth Corp / Mnemosyne Labs (the "Company"), Logan Kirkland (the "Original Author"), 
   and the Prompt Engineers Guild (the "Guild") retain exclusive, individual, and unlimited 
   rights in perpetuity to use of the Software and its derivatives in commercial projects 
   without being subject to § 3 or § 4.

§ 6. In the event of a dispute regarding the terms of this license, the parties agree to 
   resolve it through arbitration in accordance with the American Arbitration Association 
   (AAA) Commercial Arbitration Rules. The arbitration will take place in San Francisco, California, United States, Earth. A single arbitrator will be appointed to resolve the dispute. The decision of the arbitrator will be final and binding on both parties. Arbitration will be conducted in English. Each party will bear its own costs and fees unless the arbitrator decides otherwise.


